# Control Flow

## Conditionals:

```
if (condition) {
    // do something
} else if (other) {
    // do other
} else {
    // default
}
```

## Switch/Case:
```
switch (value) {
    case 1: ... break;
    case 2: ... break;
    default: ...
}
```

## Loops:

**For loop:**
```
for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    // repeat n times
}
```

**While loop:**
```
while (condition) {
    // repeat while true
}
```

**Do-While:**
```
do {
    // execute at least once
} while (condition);
```

## Control Statements:
- break: Exit loop
- continue: Skip to next iteration

# Object-Oriented Programming

## Core Concepts:

**Class:**
- Blueprint for objects
- Contains attributes and methods

**Object:**
- Instance of a class
- Has state and behavior

## Four Pillars:

| Pillar | Description |
|--------|------------|
| Encapsulation | Hide internal details |
| Inheritance | Child class inherits from parent |
| Polymorphism | Same interface, different behavior |
| Abstraction | Hide complexity |

## Example:
```
class Animal {
    String name;

    void speak() {
        // override in subclass
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void speak() {
        print("Woof!");
    }
}
```

# Programming Best Practices

## Code Quality:
- Meaningful variable names
- Consistent formatting
- Comments for complex logic
- Small, focused functions

## DRY Principle:
Don't Repeat Yourself
- Extract common code to functions
- Avoid copy-paste

## Error Handling:
```
try {
    // risky code
} catch (Exception e) {
    // handle error
} finally {
    // cleanup
}
```

## Testing:
- Unit tests: Test individual functions
- Integration tests: Test components together
- Test edge cases

## Version Control:
- Track changes (Git)
- Branches for features
- Commit often
